<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Winter Resilience in Transport</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Professor Greg Marsden and Jeremy Shires</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Institute for Transport Studies, University of Leeds (WRT 010)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key Points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However well prepared we are, some disruption from winter weather is inevitable</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In considering winter resilience it is therefore crucial to look beyond the actions of the transport system operators to minimise or manage the disruptive impacts</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Short-run disruptions often involve a large amount of rearrangement and postponement of activities. Estimates of the costs to the economy may therefore be overstated.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Greater attention should be given to developi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng adaptive capacity for travell</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and that also means greater engagement from organisations that are impacted.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Professor Marsden is the Director of the Institute for Transport Studies at the University of Leeds. He is also the Project Director for the Disruption project (</span><a href="http://www.disruptionproject.net"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.disruptionproject.net</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">), a £1.2m Research Council study examining what can be learnt from disruptive events of various sorts. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Jeremy Shires is a Senior Research Fellow at the Institute for Transport Studies at University of Leeds and had responsibility for designing and implementing all surveys undertaken as part of the Disruption project.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Disruption project conducted a large scale on-line survey (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2,417</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) in six of the worst affected areas of the UK (Hampshire, Kent, Surrey, Norfolk, South Wales and West Yorkshire) during the severe bout of winter weather in January 2013. The submission draws on the findings from this survey and broader insights from the Disruption project which has also explored flooding and infrastructure closure. The submission however represents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the views of the authors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rather than the Disruption project team or the Institute for Transport Studies.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Severe bouts of winter weather will continue to happen. Whilst it is undoubted that gritting, ploughing and better insulation of key system components can all serve to reduce the amount of time which the network is unavailable or operating at limited capacity, some disruption is inevitable. This submission focusses on how best to manage the response of people under disruption.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Behavioural Response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and Impacts</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The survey of 2013 showed a wide range of responses to the severe weather conditions. 40% of people cancelled their main activity. This leaves a further 60% which are conducted in different ways or at different times. Around one-quarter of people evaluate their journeys and carry on. A similar proportion postpone the activity to a proximate time period. Less than 10% of people try and conduct the journey by another mode, whilst just over 10% conduct their business remotely (e.g. online) and 4% switch destination (e.g. shopping more locally).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">How people respond varies quite significantly across different activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (Table 1)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Many respondents (12%) were able to work from home (noting that an on-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">line sample has a bias). A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">round 40% of commute and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> business travel were cancelled. Importantly, 40% of business trips were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> postponed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rather than cancelled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Two activities were particularly affected. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">School escort (due to school closures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – see further discussion below</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) and sporting activities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(facilities unfit for use) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">suffered the highest ra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tes of cancellation (80% &amp; 75%). C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are for others (e.g. elderly relatives) has one of the low</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">est rates of cancelations (25%) – caring trips are important to people. Some of the cancelled trips are fulfilled by others (e.g. neighbours or other family members that live closer).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Table </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1: Behavioural </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Responses – By Main Activity Affected</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:59.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Activity</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:55pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Delayed Start</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:55pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Delayed Finish</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.85pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Postponed</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:50.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cancel</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:65.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">New Destination</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.95pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conducted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Remotely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">a</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:30.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Other</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:37.3pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">n</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; bor