-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:37.3pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">95</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">Note: Rows do not add up to 100% as respondents could select more than one response. </span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">a:  Conducted at home via internet, telephone etc…</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Taken over a period of a week, there is considerable opportunity for people to reschedule activities. Even in the worst affected areas of the UK, the severe weather of January 2013 affected only one quarter of the respondents for more than 5 days. Whilst rearrangement has a time cost, it is not the case that the drop in traffic on the roads and the scenes of stranded cars are synonymous with chaos in the activities we conduct. It seems likely that the back of envelope estimates of costs to the UK economy are overstated because of the flexibilities that are exhibited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The impacts of the disruption on individuals are also widely distributed. Whilst one quarter of people reported a great deal of inconvenience, around 20% reported very little or no inconvenience.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Communicating with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Travellers</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In terms of helping travellers to respond to snow and ice, familiarity with alternatives is important for those who still feel the need to travel. 63% of respondents in our surveys were affected on journeys they typically conducted several times a week. Only 4% of people were embarking on a journey which they did less frequently than several times a year. There are therefore many opportunities to make travellers aware of alternative routing and mode choice options throughout the year.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is also considerable flexibility in altering journey departure times with around two-thirds of respondents changing the times they leave for or depart from work. Information about the likely implications of setting off at different times could clearly be helpful.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 14.11pt; padding-left:14.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Less than 20% of people reported looking at advice from one of the following: (a) National government; (b) Local government; or (c) Emergency services (Table 2). With national organisations, such as the AA or the Met Office, seemingly preferred (56%).  A key message to travellers during bad weather is to “avoid unnecessary journeys”. Of those that reported seeking such advice, 88% followed it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Table 2: Sources of Official Advice During the Disruption</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:100%"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:30.58%"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Source of Official Advice</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:14.96%"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.